<title>Told in illustration of the picture of the dance of sorcerers (Mr Stow&apos;s number 8 and 9)</title>
<summary><i>Remarks upon sorcerers, their dress, etc. (in explanation of one of Mr Stow’s copies of Bushmen paintings), by Dia!kwãin (L V.-10. 4744-4750).</i> The dance of sorcerers is called the ||<i>ken.</i> The dancers play the role of the dog and the gemsbok in the dance. The sorcerers watch to see whether the people will laugh at them or show &apos;understanding&apos; when they are dressed in this way.</summary><comments>1) Date on p.4750: 9 June, 2) p.4744v: more about the dance of the sorcerers (||<i>ken</i>), 3) p.4745v: about the rings worn in the dance, 3) p.4746v: how the people must behave towards sorcerers, 4) p.4755v: a child&apos;s knowledge or education: their parents teach them not to laugh or disrespect others who are &apos;different&apos;, 5) See also <i>Picture of Mr Orpen&apos;s</i>, 6) This story is found in Book V-10</comments><date>19 May – June 1875</date><storypages>4744-4750, 4755-4757</storypages><category>Custom and daily life</category><author>Dia!kwain (David Hoesar) (V)</author><keyword><kw>sorcerers</kw><subkw>Mr Stow&apos;s picture of the dance of sorcerers</subkw></keyword>
